remarks: This review provides little value. Determining / judging the informational value of an opinion piece that would likely not be used for academic purposes (unless in a study on the writings about it, or the opinions about the debate, in which case all of the above would change to high) would inform whether or not I use it. This is quite tricky indeed and incidentally upholds rather than undermines previous class/educational/high-lowculture debates, and so on.
I find some of these dimensions too general to make judgements in this context.

Again (and I repeat myself here) - all of this provides more or less fruitful in specific contexts (what I am writing). I'm not sure it would uphold in 'any context' - and I worry that this type of testing upholds dangerous predetermined access and promotion of pillars of knowledge that are not in line with an open society, or the values of the internet.

I was looking in measles oriented document but this document mentions measles only two times. It concentrates more on other vaccinations. Also, the time of the article is missing.
I find it difficult to asses a criterium such as "quality" if I need to write on the debate. Regardless of the quality (based on whatever quality criteria), any article is part of the debate.

This is difficult to judge. The article does prove a point but is written in a terribly patronizing and almost spiteful tone. It does point to a piece of evidence which parents might wish to consider, but could have communicated this more systematically and soberly I would say.

I find this assessment really difficult to make, since some of the quality dimensions are so subjective to assign. For example, I would describe the article as accurately describing the personal experience of the author, but not as an accurate account for my research purpose (institutional response) necessarily.

Against my previous labeling of conspiracy theory articles as tending to be unreferenced, this was a well referenced (from both news and academic sources). The document took a clear stance against anti-vaxers and did it well through its examples of historic and contemporary discussion of measles and vaccinations. The article was also accessible on a wide level and could be read by the general public, but provided links to each of its sources within the document itself.
The sources that was cited in this "source" might provide additional information. The fact that this article kept referencing other professional works made it looks reliable.

The annotation function doesn't work on iOS apparently so I didn't use that.Knowing the Huffington Post I rated the trustworthiness as 4 because there might be a liberal slant to the article that prevents them from presenting all relevant information. The document is definitely not neutral.

This example is a very short news article. Of course the length of the article does not say anything about the quality, but still the amount of words might be taken into consideration as a factor as well. This article, at least, is very poor on all given aspects.

As I am focusing on the debate and not so much on accuracy and and neutrality and so forth, this seems to be a relevant article. However, it suprises me to find ou an article like this from this source.
